Counterevidence of crime-reduction effects from federal grants of military equipment to local police
Anna Gunderson   1, Elisha Cohen   2, Kaylyn Jackson Schiff   2, Tom S. Clark   2 ✉, Adam N. Glynn2,3 and Michael Leo Owens   2
In 2017, the Trump Administration restored local law enforcement agencies’ access to military weapons and some other types of surplus military equipment (SME) that had been prohibited by the Obama Administration. The Justice Department background paper used to justify this decision cited two papers published by the American Economic Association. These papers used SME data collected with a 2014 Freedom of Information Act request and concluded that SME, supplied to local law enforcement by the federal government via the 1033 Program, reduces crime. Here we show that the findings of these studies are not credible due to problems with the data. Using more detailed audit data on 1033 SME, we show that the 2014 data are flawed and that the more recent data provide no evidence that 1033 SME reduces crime.

Militarization is a prominent development in policing across the globe1–6. In the United States, it has followed a reorientation of policing towards ‘police-invoked law enforcement’, whereby “the police themselves initiate the action in the specific instance, though sometimes in response to a general public concern over the problem, and whatever action they take is on their own authority.”7,8 Political and public debate about militarization often focuses on a number of choices and actions by police departments and sheriffs’ offices that increase their possession and deployment of military-grade or military-style equipment and attire5,9–11. Of course, the increased possession, display and use of military or military-style equipment by subnational law enforcement agencies (LEAs) has been underway for decades. Moreover, there is a history in the United States of occasionally using military forces for domestic policing at local level (for example, colonial militias, US Army control of the South during Reconstruction, National Guard deployments during the Civil Rights Movement, protests against the Vietnam War, and urban and rural unrest and riots)4–6,12. However, current trends have been particularly facilitated by federal programs that are intended to support local LEAs. Among the most important federal policies and programs that have contributed to police militarization is the provision of SME to local police and sheriffs via the 1033 Program. That program is administered by the Law Enforcement Support Office (LESO) within the Department of Defense and has its origins in the War on Drugs. However, it has evolved over time to allow local agencies to request SME for virtually any law enforcement function, including both tactical and non-tactical supplies4–6,11,13–16. Today, at least 7,000 LEAs participate, according to the LESO, and as of 2017 approximately US$7 billion worth of SME had been transferred to subnational LEAs17. This equipment ranges from ‘high-visibility’ and tactical goods immediately associated with military purposes to more general goods. For example, agencies can access vehicles and aircraft, but they can also access medical supplies or gym equipment. A majority of SME transferred comprises those more general supplies.
Despite the varied nature of the SME items the 1033 Program transfers, and that most SME items obtained by local law enforcement are not tactical, many policymakers justify the 1033 Program

on the claim that transfers of SME improve the quality and efficacy of local law enforcement activities. In particular, the Trump Administration used that claim in 2017 to reverse the 2014 restrictions the Obama Administration placed on the program, which banned transfers of military-grade weapons and some other prominent military equipment. Given the policy claim and its influence, and the 1033 Program’s importance in contributing to militarization of local police and sheriffs, social scientists seek to identify the positive (and negative) effects of the program.
Generally, however, rigorous empirical studies of the causes and consequences of the variation in the transfers of SME to local LEAs via the 1033 Program are nascent18–27. This is unfortunate, because whether the militarization of local LEAs, particularly through the 1033 Program, especially affects crime in cities and counties is an important empirical matter, one with civic, policy and normative implications. One reason for the lack of evidence about the effects of the 1033 Program on US policing is the lack of public, high-quality data on SME transfers. Indeed, it was only in 2014 that the federal government made public 1033 Program data, though the data the government released were crudely aggregated. We show that those data were fundamentally flawed for empirical research and public policymaking. Since the release of the 2014 data, the two most prominent and cited studies, published together in 2017, report a range of positive effects from the 1033 Program22,23. In both studies, which received broad media and policymaker attention, the research question is the effect of the aggregate amount of SME— value and quantity of items—sent to a county. The reported benefits include reductions in all types of crime, without negative effects on case closure rates, arrest rates or assaults and injuries to officers, as well as reductions in citizen complaints against the police and declines in civilian assaults and deaths of police officers22,23.
More granular agency-level data on SME from the 1033 Program exist to allow scholars to better assess the robustness of past empirical findings. It has been publicly available for a while, though few scholars have accessed it. Others may have been unaware of its existence. A notable exception that relies on these less crudely aggregated agency data reports that the 1033 Program has an even larger effect on crime reduction than what earlier studies found20. In terms

