Indeed, scholars motivated by this type of concern have gone beyond the proximate effects of SME to report effects as theoretically tenuous as a decrease in suicide rates30 or reductions in charitable giving and volunteering among Black Americans31. Other studies observe that police militarization may produce adverse effects for communities20,24–26. Most notably, an analysis of the deployment of special weapons and tactics (SWAT) teams finds that police militarization neither reduces crime nor decreases harm to officers by civilians but may harm public attitudes about the police (for example, support for funding or perceived legitimacy, confidence and trust in the police)26.
There are at least three explanations for the conflicting results of previous studies of the effects of the militarization of local law enforcement. First, the form of militarization differs across studies. This is most obvious when comparing studies focusing narrowly on SWAT data versus studies that rely on 2014 SME data from the 1033 Program22,23,26. However, even among the studies that solely use 1033 Program data, there can be differences in findings due to the existence of multiple categories of SME, including weapons, optics, radar and vehicles. Local LEAs’ stock of 1033 Program equipment varies greatly across these categories, with some categories of equipment yielding different effects on, for instance, crime rates. Both of the studies we focus on below disaggregate total SME by key categories and report differential effects by categories of equipment.
Second, empirical studies have used different units of analysis. As noted, the most prominent studies analyse county-level relationships between SME and public safety outcomes22,23. However, because the majority of decisions regarding the procurement of SME are made below the county level, at the level of independent local LEAs, the use of county-level data raises a concern of ecological bias. In particular, if crime rates are declining for urban agencies and SME transfers are large for suburban agencies in the same counties, then county-level analysis would mistakenly attribute the urban crime reduction to the suburban use of SME. Hence, county-level measures of SME create a serious challenge to inference, a key issue we discuss in detail below. It is in this spirit that the more recent studies making use of agency-level data advance the study of SME20,24,29. However, at the same time, other studies aggregate even further to state level21,25,32,33. For instance, one study makes the case for a state-level analysis based on states’ oversight, accountability and use of SME from the 1033 Program31. However, it is unclear how much of a role or influence states have in the decision by local LEAs—city and county police departments and sheriffs’ offices—to apply for 1033 Program aid34.
Third, while most studies of local law enforcement militarization focus on the distribution of SME from the 1033 Program (for the exception, see Mummolo26), they tend to measure militarization differently. Studies can use the quantity of SME the 1033 Program transfers to agencies, municipalities and counties, or they can use the monetary value of SME transferred to localities22,23. In addition to these three reasons that we identify for inconsistent findings from

existing empirical research, a fourth reason may best explain the disparate findings: the 2014 federal data from the 1033 Program, based on a Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request by National Public Radio (NPR), are deeply flawed.
However, the federal government does collect cleaner, more comprehensive, and disaggregated data. Given the availability of these richer data, we have two related and original goals in this article. First, we assess the validity of government records about SME transfers to local LEAs. Second, we test the robustness of the high-profile empirical findings and revisit a main empirical claim on which federal policymaking has rested, and even altered federal policymaking across presidential administrations—that SME transfers from the 1033 Program reduce crime. Our findings suggest that any extant conclusions that the transfer of SME via the 1033 Program to cities and counties causes lower crime rates are likely driven by faulty data. We also demonstrate key barriers to generating credible assessments of the effects, whether positive or negative, of SME support for local law enforcement.
We focus exclusively on the effects of SME on crime rates for a number of reasons. First, it is that effect that has featured most prominently in political and policy debates. As noted above, the claim that the 1033 Program reduces crime was at the centre of the Trump Administration’s justification for undoing Obama-era limitations to the transfer of SME to local police and sheriffs. And, it is that finding that scholars have most consistently analysed across different empirical studies20,22,23. Second, many of the civic outcomes that previous studies have considered at the county or state level are either difficult or impossible to measure at local level. As it is, accurately measuring crime rates is a particularly fraught undertaking35. Indeed, the citizen complaint data reported in one previous study are, in fact, not even aggregated at the county level but rather selected from a non-random single jurisdiction from within each county23. (We learned this through personal correspondence with the authors of the original study.) Therefore, to the extent that our analysis calls into question prior empirical findings about crime rates, we believe there is room for future work beyond the scope of a single study to revisit the entire literature on the effects of SME on public safety and other civic consequences.
Our results contravene extant findings that militarization of police and sheriffs necessarily makes the community better. In particular, in this article, we find no evidence that federal distributions of SME to local LEAs across the United States reduce crime rates, neither violent nor nonviolent crime rates, in the jurisdictions that receive it. Consequently, we posit that, because of serious data problems and debatable methodological choices in prior studies, the empirical foundations on which social scientists, along with policymakers and the public, stand when making causal claims about the effects of the transfers of SME may be no firmer than quicksand.
Results
Our analysis comprises two related tasks. First, we use two different data releases by LESO to assess the quality of government SME records. Second, we assess the robustness of empirical claims about the effects of SME on crime reduction given the data problems we document. As we detail below, there are considerable discrepancies in the data about which LEAs have and use SME. Moreover, while the more recent audit data represent an important improvement over previous records—indicating the agencies that received the equipment, not just the county to which it was shipped—they still suffer from one important limitation, namely that any equipment that was obtained by a department but subsequently destroyed, lost or returned will not appear in these audits, because they only capture what is currently in local law enforcement possession. And, unfortunately, it is not possible to completely reconstruct the data. We attempted to, by filing a request pursuant to the FOIA (case number DLA-DSERV2018-005182; details and response included

