Data discrepancies. With the agency-level data in hand, we can better describe the geographic distribution of SME. We are also able to identify a number of problems with the county-level data. That is, we can identify systematic inconsistencies between the two different versions of the data on which scholars have relied.
Figure 1 shows the location of each agency that received a transfer of SME from the DLA between 2010 and 2015. The points show the location of the agency, and the colour corresponds to the total amount, in US dollars, of the value of the transfers to each agency—darker colours indicate more aid. In general, there seem to be some patterns, such as more transfers going to more populous parts of the country. At the same time, there is some interesting variation not necessarily associated with population. The State of Mississippi, for example, stands out for its relative lack of transfers, as do Virginia, North Carolina and West Virginia. There have been a large amount of transfers to Appalachia and the coastal parts of the Mid-Atlantic region.
There could be a number of reasons explaining the geographic variation in the distribution of this equipment. Some past work assumes that the acquisition of equipment is affected by an agency’s proximity to one of the major distribution centres, because agencies

acquiring SME are responsible for transporting the SME or paying for shipping. In addition, there is variation in the costs to an agency for participating in the program—some states charge a flat fee to individual agencies for administering the program, whereas other states charge a rate based on the assessed value of the SME acquired. Of course, there are also budgetary explanations, such as the agencies’ fiscal stress—departments with fewer resources might be compelled to rely on SME more than are departments that have the ability to purchase their own equipment. Related, given the scarcity of high-value items available from the DLA, there is a large random component to whether an agency acquires a piece of equipment, which is affected by the amount of time and energy the agency can devote to searching and writing justifications for equipment. Finally, and especially in the aftermath of the 2016 events we describe above, one might expect that local political conditions influence a department’s capacity to make use of the program.
