Inconsistent item records. In some instances, the original data report items that have been transferred to a county, but we cannot locate such an item in the more recent inventory, even while we can locate a similar item in that county. In Table 1, for example, we describe two vehicles, one which was reported in the county-level data and the other in the agency-level data, with similar shipping dates, but different serial numbers. Because there are several discrepancies across the two datasets, it is not possible to determine the extent of this problem.
State agencies. Equipment shipped to state agencies, which can ultimately be deployed anywhere in a state, are associated with only the county to which it was shipped. This will result in an inflated level of military aid to counties with state agency receiving locations. We identified non-local agencies by filtering agency names with words such as ‘state agencies’, ‘state departments’ (parks and recreations or correctional departments), or ‘multi-county or multi-agency task

forces’. In our data, there are 125 unique agencies that match these characteristics, for a total of 8,175 observations, accounting for roughly 5% of our dataset.
While we cannot determine the exact cause of these discrepancies, recent media reports and a government study highlight the lack of rigorous controls to track this equipment which can result in (a) unreported transfers of equipment from one agency to another, (b) equipment being lost or damaged but not reported or (c) poor record keeping of the equipment transferred in the first instance. For example, in a sting operation, the Government Accountability Office was able to create a fictitious LEA and gained permission to receive over US$1 million in military surplus equipment17. In addition, because the original data only report the county to which equipment is shipped, it is possible that there are items that have been shipped to one county on behalf of an agency located in another county. For example, we have learned of instances in which aircraft and vehicles have first been sent to one location for repair, other maintenance or even training, before being ultimately directed to the agency that has custody of the equipment.

