The implication of these various discrepancies is that the data released by the LESO program are unreliable and ill-suited to systematic analysis of the effects of SME on law enforcement outcomes. Most alarming is that only 2% of the data can be matched exactly across the two data releases. In conjunction with the myriad other problems we identify, we have no reason to believe that either version of the data is comprehensive or valid, though there do seem to be greater problems with the county-level data.
Replication analyses. Our replications focus on two prominent studies that were published simultaneously in the American Economic Journal. We focus on them because of (a) the broad media coverage of their findings and (b) the use of their findings by the Trump Administration to justify revoking limitations that the Obama Administration imposed on the 1033 Program, including prohibitions against the transfer of certain types of SME to local LEAs. For instance, on 28 August 2017, then-US Attorney General Jeff Sessions spoke before the National Fraternal Order of Police, remarking in defense of the Trump Administration’s recent full restoration of the 1033 Program that “Studies have shown [surplus military] equipment reduces crime rates, reduces the number of assaults against police officers, and reduces the number of complaints against police officers. Those restrictions went too far. We will not put superficial concerns above public safety.”
Specifically, we conduct the same analyses presented in Bove and Gavrilova (BG)22 and Harris, Park, Bruce and Murray (HPBM)23, using the agency-level data. We conduct three separate analyses for each study: first, using the authors’ code and data, we replicate their published results exactly. Second, we attempt to replicate their findings using our agency data, aggregated to the county (more details on this in the Supplementary Methods). Finally, we use the more recently released DLA data to estimate the relationship between 1033 Program disbursements and crime rates at the agency level. Both BG and HPBM use instrumental variables in their analysis, and we calculate identical instrumental variables in our data using their methods. The first-stage results for both analyses, as well as the full replication tables, are given in the Supplementary Results. For the original BG analysis, our county-level replication and our agency-level replication, all first-stage results are positive and significant. We also note that both our aggregated county-level and agency-level replications provide larger first-stage estimates, and as in the original BG analyses have F statistics far above 10 (the typical rule of thumb for a sufficiently strong instrument). For the original HPBM analysis, only some of the coefficients on the individual instruments were significant in the first stage of both the item and value analyses, but the F statistic was significant for both analyses. That said, for the original HPBM analysis, the F statistic for the value analysis was below 10. For our aggregated county-level first-stage replication analyses, none of the individual instruments were significant, but as with HPBM, the F statistics were significant for both the item and value analyses. Additionally, the F statistic from our aggregated county-level value analysis was below 10 but larger than that from HPBM, while the F statistic from our aggregated county-level item analysis was just below 10. Finally, for our agency-level first-stage replication analyses, again none of the individual instruments were significant, but the F statistics were significant and well above 10 for both the item and value analyses.
BG seek to understand the effect of militarization aid on a variety of outcomes such as arrest rates, offenders killed and civilian complaints, among others. For our purposes, we focus on their analysis of the effect of military aid on a variety of county crime rates—total, homicide, robbery, assault, burglary, larceny and vehicle theft. To ensure we have complete coverage on the number of jurisdictions that could request equipment from the federal government, in the replication we include all cities and all counties in all states that reported crime data, the main outcome variable of interest. Though

there are over 19,000 local jurisdictions across the 50 states, just over 9,000 of those reported crime data to the national government. (Formally, there are 19,354 ‘incorporated places’ in the United States as of 2018.) Therefore, our sample includes the approximately 9,000 agencies reporting crime data which could potentially request SME through the 1033 Program.
Figure 3 summarizes the results of our three analyses: the replicated results from BG, our replicated analysis aggregating the agency-level data to the county level (the same unit as BG) and our analysis run at the agency level. In each analysis, we employ their exact research design, but use different data and/or units of analysis. Our results, both in the replication county estimations and the agency-level estimations, differ substantially from those of BG. We find no clear evidence of a significant effect of military aid on a variety of crime rates. For our preferred agency-level analysis, many of our point estimates are positive (that is, the opposite direction from BG), and those that are negative are insignificant. For our aggregated county-level analysis, most of the coefficients are negative, but insignificant. The two significant negative coefficients (for robbery and burglary) are barely significant and are accompanied by agency-level estimates that are insignificant and of the wrong sign. Furthermore, this pattern of insignificance does not seem to be simply a matter of low power. In the Supplementary Information, we show that our analysis is generally well powered. Additionally, in all crime categories, at least one of our estimates has tighter confidence bounds and higher power than the original BG analysis. Therefore, even if the NPR FOIA data were valid and the BG research design perfect, it is more likely that the BG findings are due to an underpowered design overstating an effect than that our null findings are due to a lack of power37. Additionally, using the equivalence test approach of Gross38 and Rainey39, we find that we can rule out substantively large effect sizes, as well as all of the significant effects presented in BG (see the Supplementary Results for details).
As with BG, HPBM study how military transfers affect crime rates of varying types. They also analyse the effect on other outcomes, including citizen complaints, assaults on officers and arrest rates. For the purposes of this replication, however, we focus solely on their analysis regarding crime rates. Also as in BG, HPBM identify this relationship at the county level. We again replicate their study using their design and our more recent data. Figure 4 reports the results of this exercise.
Our analysis yields no support for HPBM’s finding of significant and negative relationships between the logged number of items given to counties and robbery, assault and vehicle theft rates. We find no statistically significant effect on those, or any other, categories of crime rates. Indeed, when we aggregate data to the county level, we only find qualitatively similar results in the analysis of homicides, though even those results do not support the claim that SME reduces crime. The county-level results seem to be driven by different patterns in jurisdictions within counties receiving more aid relative to those receiving less (or no) aid. When aggregated, that heterogeneity is masked, and one draws the incorrect conclusion that places receiving more aid experience lower crime rates. Similarly, if we instead examine the logged value of items, HPBM find a significant and negative relationship between military equipment transfers and robbery, assault and vehicle theft rates, whereas we find no significant negative effect of the value of military equipment transfers on a variety of crime rates.
Specifically, in all of these analyses, we typically find no evidence of an effect, and in our preferred agency-level analysis, many of our point estimates are positive (that is, the opposite direction from HPBM), and those that are negative are insignificant (with the exception of the value-based analysis for robbery). For our aggregated county-level analysis, most of the coefficients are negative, but insignificant. The two significant negative coefficients (for

