and behaviour are associated with intergovernmental transfers of SME. A key concern is whether SME transfers to police and sheriffs are consequential for public safety, either positively or negatively. After all, the primary policy assumption for SME transfers is that they produce a net positive for public safety.
Past empirical studies of police militarization in the United States have concluded that SME transfers to local police and sheriffs cut crime22,23. They claim, too, that such transfers reduce injuries to officers and have no adverse effects on civilian injuries or complaints about local law enforcement officer behaviour. Our study, however, which includes replication of key studies and leverages refined data measuring SME transfers, invites reconsideration of prior conclusions and claims.
We highlight the measurement problems of prior data on SME transfers via the 1033 Program, which the DLA maintains and shares. We also produce empirical findings that contradict key extant studies. As a result, our analysis counsels against drawing firm conclusions and promoting claims about the positive policy efficacy of police militarization in general, and via the 1033 Program in particular, especially for crime rates, which is the most important policy concern.
Based on our empirical findings, we recommend that policymakers and social scientists seeking to make reliable claims about police militarization employ more recent and limited but far cleaner and more valid data on SME transfers26. Additionally, our findings suggest that scholars and policymakers would benefit from a more rigorous effort to obtain systematic data on the kinds of accountable, controlled, military-grade equipment that local LEAs possess, both SME from the 1033 Program and other equipment purchased via financial subsidies of other government programs (for example, Urban Area Security Initiative grants) and local source revenue. That is important: just as we lack systematic, comprehensive and accessible data on police use of force against civilians, we lack similar data on the kinds of enhanced or high-level military-oriented equipment supplied to police and sheriffs by and beyond the US military.
Improving the empirical basis for justifying (or critiquing) police militarization is important. As past studies of the United States recognize, the civic (and political) effects of policing, generally, are widespread but often more deeply felt by some communities relative to others. Police officers and sheriffs are ubiquitous representatives of the state and, therefore, have an out-sized effect on how citizens perceive and experience government. While we focus here on the effects of police militarization on crime rates, our results should also cause us to question similar analyses that claim to find no evidence of deleterious effects of militarization on citizen perceptions of and interactions with the police.
Methods
We seek to assess the quality and validity of government SME transfer records and to replicate and evaluate the robustness of high-profile empirical findings that claim that SME transfers from the 1033 Program reduce crime. The sections below detail the relevant processes and estimation strategies used for each of these components of our analysis, with further detail provided in the Supplementary Methods. Note that all statements of statistical significance are based on two-tailed tests.
Assessing the quality and validity of SME transfer records. The most prominent studies of the effects of SME rely on data that report items shipped from the DLA and the county in which the recipient was located. This dataset was released by the LESO of the DLA in response to a FOIA request by NPR. However, the government also requires that LEAs report quarterly inventories of the SME they have in their possession, a process that was formalized and required by law by the FY2017 Defense Authorization Act. The availability of these agency-level data allows us to not only compare the county-level records from the NPR FOIA data used by previous studies with the agency-item LESO inventory, but also to generally assess the quality, reliability and validity of the LESO SME transfer records. The DLA did not retain records of agency inventories before 2014; therefore, for earlier years, we must reconstruct the inventories using what information is contained in

subsequent inventories. For those years, therefore, our estimates of SME for each agency are a lower bound on how much SME each agency had.
Reliability concerns. Through attempting to match item records between these datasets and through communication with Kenneth (Ken) MacNevin, the Chief Spokesperson for DLA Disposition Services, we identified the many inconsistencies between the NPR FOIA data and the LESO inventory data discussed in this article and detailed in Tables 1 and 2 and Fig. 2 (more information about the complexities in working with this militarization data is provided in the Supplementary Methods). To more thoroughly document the extent to which these inconsistencies arise, we also match on NSN, county, state and shipping date to see how the values for the same items shipped on the same day to the same county differ across datasets. In the data, only 2% are exact matches (having positive values of aid in both datasets), though nearly 8% are exact matches when we include observations in the NPR dataset with an item value of zero (that is, there is an item for that county–NSN–day in the NPR dataset with a listed value of zero, but we do not have any item listed for that day). Nearly 78% of the data is on the y axis (no record in the LESO dataset but a positive record in the NPR dataset), while 7.4% is on the x axis (a positive value in the LESO data but nothing listed in the NPR data). While the records missing from the LESO inventory dataset can be explained by uncontrolled items dropping off of the inventory after a year, as is the procedure for relinquishing control of those generic office equipment items to the LEA, the items missing from the NPR dataset but in the LESO inventory suggest important inconsistencies between the controlled items recorded in the two datasets. Moreover, Supplementary Figs. 4–7 map the differences between the military aid data used by BG and HPBM, revealing inconsistencies, likely differences in interpretation and other potential problems even in working with the (assumed) same county-level SME transfer records. These inconsistencies and the other problems that we document suggest caution in working with these records of SME transfers.
Ecological fallacy concerns. Furthermore, a particular concern in working with the NPR FOIA data is that all item shipment records provide only the name of the county to which the equipment was shipped, rather than indicating the specific local LEA that requested the item. The immediate cause of concern, then, is a matter of ecological fallacy. In this setting, an ecological fallacy would occur if, for example, military aid was going disproportionately to more suburban or rural parts of a county, while crime rates were decreasing in the more urban parts of the county, or vice versa. A county-level analysis would indicate a positive correlation between military equipment and crime reduction, while an agency-level analysis would indicate a negative correlation between military equipment and crime reduction. Note, the concern here is not about ecological displacement, where the effect of militarization simply shifts the location of crime elsewhere. The concern about ecological fallacy can be driven by heterogeneity among jurisdictions in changes in crime rates (even unrelated to militarization), which is masked when agency-level data are aggregated to the county level. Under conditions such as the example we offer, inaccurate inferences about those jurisdictions may follow from analysing county-level data. The agency-level data provided by the LESO inventories avoid this problem and allow us to replicate the results of previous studies at both the county and agency level, described more below. Differences in the county-level results and the agency-level results suggest ecological fallacy concerns, as well as the influence of the data inconsistencies that we describe.
General replication approach. We replicate and extend the two most prominent studies of the effects of the 1033 Program, namely BG and HPBM, using more recent, agency-level SME transfer data. Thus, the sources of data that we use are the authors’ datasets and replication code, the agency-item dataset representing LESO’s 1033 Program inventory that we downloaded on 31 March 2018, the Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI)’s Uniform Crime Reporting (UCR) Program data used by the previous studies and demographic data from the Census Bureau also used by the previous studies. With the LESO inventory data, we construct an agency-level dataset and also aggregate to the county level for a county-level dataset (more information about the construction of our datasets is provided in the Supplementary Methods).
Sample and time period. To use the LESO inventory data, we first needed to match the agency-level data to jurisdictions. We used the Google Maps application programming interface to search for the name of each agency and retrieve its address, locality, latitude and longitude. These pieces of information allow us to link the agency to a specific jurisdiction (city or town) and county. Then, while the agency-level data provide us with information for agencies participating in the 1033 Program, they obviously do not provide us with information for agencies not participating in the program. In other words, we only have those agencies for which there were any military transfers. We are left to construct the set of jurisdictions that received no military transfers. To overcome this issue, we rely on the universe of cities that report crime rates to the FBI. This is neither the universe of agencies receiving military transfers nor the universe of agencies in the United States. The sample in our data, then, is the set of agencies reporting crime rates to the FBI. While we have no reason to believe that this constitutes a random sample

