In regards to the time period of study, the BG county-level data span from 2006 to 2012, and the HPBM county-level data span from 2000 to 2013. However, in our main results, we use replication agency-level data from 2010 to 2015 and replication county-level data from 2010 to 2014. We use these different time periods for our replication data because they represent the most recent years of data available through the more recent LESO inventory release and because of data limitations with the UCR series. Therefore our sample size is determined by the number of agencies reporting crime rates over this time period. Nonetheless, in Section 2.7 of the Supplementary Information, we also run our analyses subsetting all data to 2010 to 2012, as these are the years for which we have overlap across all of the datasets. With this smaller but more comparable set of observations, we find similar results to our main results. We still do not find that military aid reduces crime rates at either the county or agency level.

Discussion of mechanisms and limitations. One potential alternative mechanism is that an increase in equipment from the 1033 Program displaces, but does not decrease, violent crime. If this is the effect that BG and HPBM are finding, it would have to be that criminal activity is being displaced across county lines in order to see the relationship between an increase in 1033 equipment and a decrease in violent crime. (One study suggests that SME might contribute to crime displacement20.) Additionally, this relationship should still be visible in our agency-level approach, but is not. Displacement is not the same thing as a reduction in crime, and so even if these studies’ conclusions are sound, they do not support the public policy justification for the 1033 Program.
HPBM argue that their findings are the result of a deterrence mechanism whereby increasing 1033 equipment deters crime. In support of this mechanism, they discuss how the relationship between the instrument and total aid is stronger for counties that received aid for multiple years. However, this would suggest that we should see a very strong deterrence effect in our data which occurs later as agencies and counties have had 1033 equipment for potentially many more years. The fact that we find no such effect suggests either that this mechanism is not supported or that 1033 equipment can deter crime for only a few years. Even if the latter is true, it again is weak justification for the 1033 Program.
While we do not find evidence supporting the claim that an increase in 1033 equipment by police is associated with a decrease in crime, we caution against drawing strong conclusions for no association as well. With the problems and inconsistencies we have documented in the data, we would be hesitant to draw strong conclusions from any analyses using these data.

Replication of BG. To disentangle the effect of police militarization on crime from a likely endogenous relationship, BG employ an instrument that combines information about military spending by the federal government and previous acquisitions of SME by counties. Specifically, they construct a variable by interacting a county’s likelihood of receiving any SME with US military spending, as a county is only eligible to receive that aid if federal military spending is sufficiently high in the previous year. They sum the quantity of items received by each county and divide that number by the lagged amount of military spending by the US government. Essentially, this allows the authors to compare counties that frequently receive aid with counties that rarely do, in years following high US military spending relative to those following lower military spending.
