Behavioural & social sciences study design

All studies must disclose on these points even when the disclosure is negative.

Study description

This study uses quantitative data on 1033 Program transfers and crime rates to analyze how militarization (via 1033 Program transfers) affects crime rates.

Research sample

We primarily use two existing datasets: the 1033 Program data publicly available through the DLA. We use the version from March 31, 2018. Link to the current version of the data: https://www.dla.mil/DispositionServices/Offers/Reutilization/LawEnforcement/ PublicInformation/ Second, we use the FBI Uniform Crime Reports data series for city and county crime rates. Link to the website: https://www.fbi.gov/ services/cjis/ucr

Sampling strategy

Our sample size is determined by the number of agencies reporting crime rates over this time period. We then link those agencies that report crime rates to DLA militarization records.

Data collection

We collected the data from the public sources identified above and stored them on a shared Dropbox.

Timing

We collected the data from the public sources identified above in spring 2018 onto a shared Dropbox.

Data exclusions

In our main analyses, we exclude agencies with crime rates over 1 million (1-3 observations), though we include all observations in our supplementary materials. Otherwise, no data is excluded from the two public datasets identified above (pending that they matched accurately across datasets).

Non-participation

No participants dropped out or declined participation.

Randomization

Participants were not allocated into experimental groups.

